data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you also inspect the exception:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // optional: verify details
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- `[ExpectedException]` is obsolete — it can't distinguish *which* line threw
- `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` scopes the assertion to the exact call
- You can inspect the exception (message, param name, inner exception)

Use `Assert.Throws<T>` if you want to match derived exception types too.
